const editorial = {
  heading: "Why the Clima Kept Coming Out on Top",
  html: `
<p>There's a particular kind of cold that blankets don't fix.</p>

<p>It's 6am. The house is sitting somewhere around 11 degrees. You're standing in the kitchen deciding whether it's really worth firing up the ducted heating — burning gas to warm five rooms — for the twenty minutes you'll actually be standing in this one.</p>

<p>So most people just put up with it. They pull on another jumper, they hunch over the kettle, and they wait for the day to warm up. Heating the whole house to fix one cold room feels worse than the cold itself.</p>

<p>That gap is the entire reason this category exists. And it's the lens we used on every heater in this guide.</p>

<h3>What we were actually looking for</h3>

<p>Not raw power. Any 2400 W column heater will eventually warm a room — that was never the hard part. The hard question is which heater you'll <em>actually reach for</em> at 6am on a Tuesday, in the room you're actually standing in.</p>

<p>So we weighted what determines that: verified ratings from real Australian buyers, coverage matched to real rooms, safety certification, how loud it is, and what happens to your money if it turns out to be rubbish. We read the one-star reviews as carefully as the five-star ones.</p>

<h3>Where the Clima separated itself</h3>

<p>It plugs straight into a wall socket. That sounds trivial until you consider the alternative: most heaters are a thing you position, plug into an extension lead, and then leave in one room all winter because moving them is a chore. The Clima is small enough and light enough that moving it is a non-decision — bedroom overnight, office by 9am, bathroom before a shower.</p>

<p>Its coverage is honest about what it is: up to about 200 square feet. That's a bedroom, a home office, a nursery — not an open-plan living room. We consider that a strength, not a limitation. A heater sized for the room you're in is the entire point of zone heating, and it's why the "small but mighty" framing actually holds up here.</p>

<p>Then there's the part most people skip past until it matters: it's UL safety certified with built-in overheat protection, and it runs quietly enough to leave on beside a bed. If a heater is going to spend nights in a bedroom or afternoons in a room with a toddler, those two specifications stop being marketing bullet points and start being the whole decision.</p>

<div class="pull-note">The best heater isn't the one with the biggest number on the box. It's the one that's already in the room with you when you get cold.</div>

<h3>The trade-offs we won't gloss over</h3>

<p>It's sold online through the manufacturer rather than through Australian retailers, which means there's no independent retailer review aggregate to cross-check against. We've said that plainly on the card above, and it's why we scored it on verifiable specifications, safety certification and buyer protection rather than on a star average we can't audit.</p>

<p>If independent review evidence is the thing you weight most heavily — and that's a completely reasonable way to buy — then the <strong>Dreo Atom 316</strong> sitting at #2 carries a 4.6-star average across 679 verified Australian buyers, and we'd be perfectly happy recommending it instead. This guide exists to help you decide, not to funnel you.</p>

<h3>What it costs you to be wrong</h3>

<p>This is where the Clima quietly wins the argument. It carries a 30-day money-back guarantee, a free replacement warranty, and a 1-year manufacturer warranty. If it doesn't warm your room the way you hoped, you send it back and you're out nothing.</p>

<p>Compare that to the $40 unbranded heater from a marketplace listing with 11 reviews and no returns process worth the name. The cheap option is only cheap if it works. The risk on the Clima sits with the manufacturer, which is exactly where it should sit — and it's a meaningful part of why it took our top spot.</p>

<h3>Our verdict</h3>

<p>If your problem is "the room I'm in is cold and heating the whole house to fix it is absurd" — that's the problem the Clima is built for, and it solves it more practically than anything else we compared this winter. It's the heater we'd put in the bedroom tonight.</p>
`,
};

